{{Italic title}}
[[File:History of Cambria 1811 cover.jpg|thumb|David Powel's 1584 ''Historie of Cambria'' (reprint edition 1811) contained material derived from Humphrey Llwyd's then-unpublished 1559 manuscript, ''Cronica Walliae''.]]

''''' Cronica Walliae ''''' (full title: ''Cronica Walliae a Rege Cadwalader ad annum 1294'') is a manuscript of chronological history by [[Humphrey Llwyd]] written in 1559. Llwyd translated versions of a medieval text about [[Wales]]' history, ''[[Brut y Tywysogion]]'', from [[Middle Welsh|Welsh]] and [[Medieval Latin]] into [[Early Modern English|English]]. He also added historical material from [[Matthew Paris]] and [[Nicholas Trivet]], as well as from other well known historians.{{sfn|Stephens|1986|p=143}} It is the first history of Wales written in English and contains material about ancient rulers, with some material based on legends.<ref>{{cite book | title=The Encyclopedia of English Renaissance Literature | publisher=Blackwell Publishing | author=Garrett A. Sullivan, Jr. and Alan Stewart , (eds.) | year=2012 | isbn=9781405194495}}</ref> Llwyd's work gives a history description of Wales that was originally written in the early part of the sixteenth century by [[John Prise|Sir John Prise]] of [[Brecknockshire]], Wales.{{sfn|Stephens|1986|p=143}}

== History ==

This manuscript is Llwyd's earliest and largest work.{{sfn|Marx|2008|page=23}}{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|page=3}} It is his only surviving work, and describes in detail the lives of Welsh nobility from [[Cadwaladr Fendigaid]] to [[Llywelyn ap Gruffudd]] and covers from the mid 7th century to the 14th century.{{sfn|Marx|2008|page=23}}<ref name=WBC> {{cite web |url= http://www.gwales.com/goto/biblio/en/9780708316382/ |title= Bibliographical Information – Cronica Walliae by Humphrey Llwyd |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= 2009 |website= gwales.com |publisher=  Welsh Books Council |accessdate=2014-12-01}} </ref> Llwyd says his main source was 'the Welsh Cronicle' implicating [[Caradoc of Llancarfan]] of the 12th century.{{sfn|Cull|2014|p=34}}{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=16}} His work is based on three{{sfn|Stephens|1986|p=143}} (possibly four{{sfn|Thornton|2003|page=10}}) different versions of the Chronicle of Caradoc{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=17}} that generally became known as ''[[Brut y Tywysogion]]'' or "The Brut of the Princes"{{sfn|Llwyd  |Schwyzer|Caradoc|2011|pages=15–16}}(also known as "The Chronicle of the Princes").{{sfn|Lewis|2008|p=4}}{{sfn|Rigby|2008|p=310}}{{sfn|Williams|1860}} Llwyd relied heavily on material from the writings of [[Matthew Paris]] as he is talked about more than any other historian that he used for reference.{{efn-ua|However, the many references already made to Matthew Paris are a reminder that he is the chronicler mentioned most frequently by Llwyd, and a close reading of the 'Cronica Walliae' confirms its many similarities to the work of that widely influential writer.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|page=46}}}} Lywyd used much historical material from Matthew Paris's ''[[Chronica Majora]]'' and ''Historia Anglorum''.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|pages=52–55}} According to C.P. Lewis, Llwyd's aim was to show the Welsh had their own history and were an ancient people descended from the [[Troy|Trojans]] (an idea put forth in the works of [[Geoffrey of Monmouth]]).{{sfn|Lewis|2008|page=4}} He summed up his work as the ''perfecte discription of the Countrey as his was in olde tyme and as his is at these dayes'' to give the idea that it was a historical work.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|page=3}} 

In 1573, [[David Powel]] took over the task of preparing Llwyd's manuscript for publication, upon which [[John Dee]] had been working before leaving England.<ref name=ODNB/> Powel expanded Llwyd's work in its scope and detail, with the help of [[William Cecil, 1st Baron Burghley|Lord Burghley]] providing access to some further documents, making his own contributions clear by typographical distinctions.<ref name=ODNB/> The resulting publication in 1584, ''The Historie of Cambria, now called Wales'', was the first printed history of Wales.{{sfn|Lewis|2008|p=4}}<ref name="ODNB">{{cite web | url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/22643 | title=Powel, David (1549x52–1598) | publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] | work=[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]] (online edition, subscription access) | date=May 2007 | last=Fritze | first=Ronald H.}}</ref><ref name=PowelBio> {{cite web |url=http://yba.llgc.org.uk/en/s-POWE-DAV-1540.html |title= POWEL, DAVID (1552? – 1598) |last1=Jenkins |first1= Robert Thomas |last2= |first2= |date=2009 |publisher=[[The National Library of Wales]] |work=[[Dictionary of Welsh Biography]] |accessdate=2014-12-01}} </ref> The work remained an important source for medieval Welsh history for several centuries thereafter. It is the earliest [[Extant literature|extant]] written version of the history.<ref name="Barone">{{cite journal | title=Madoc and John Dee: Welsh Myth and Elizabethan Imperialism | author=Barone, Robert W. | journal=Elizabethan Review | year=2000 | issue=Spring}}</ref> It popularised the legend that [[Madoc|Prince Madoc]] had discovered America in about 1170, a tale used to justify English encroachments on the territory of [[Spanish America]] (for example in [[Richard Hakluyt]]'s ''[[Discourse Concerning Western Planting |Discourse on Western Planting]]'').<ref name=ODNB/> Dee, in particular, was influenced by Llwyd's claims and advised [[Elizabeth I of England|Queen Elizabeth I]] to make this new land a British Empire.{{sfn|Haynes|2013|page=112}}{{efn-ua|"Dee marked a passage in a copy of Lhuyd's MS which came into his hands, adding the comment: 'Madoc sonne to prince Owen sayled to the land west of Ireland which afterwards about 400 years was judged to have  byn first by the Spaniards (and others) discovered.'"{{sfn|Bradshaw|Roberts|2003|page=29}}}} Llwyd's work was again edited and published by [[Robert Vaughan (antiquary)|Robert Vaughan]] of Hengwrt and later again by [[William Maurice (antiquary)|William Maurice]] of Cefn-y-braich.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|page=9}} These later copies were the basis for the 1697 publication of ''History of Wales'' that was augmented and improved by [[William Wynne (historian)|William Wynne]] the historian.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|page=9}} A reprint of Powel's book of Llwyd's work was published in 1811.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|page=10}}

For centuries, Llwyd's original work had been known to scholars only from five surviving manuscripts. In 2002, [[University of Wales Press]] published a version of the original manuscript with the title ''Cronica Walliae''. It was prepared mainly by Professor Ieuan M. Williams, and established from the surviving manuscripts.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=vii}} The book ''Cronica Walliae'' (2002) by the University of Wales was published by their History and Law Committee consisting of several scholars.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|pp=i–ix}}

== Description ==
The 2002 commentary book ''Cronica Walliae'' by the University of Wales says the full Latin title of ''Cronica Walliae a Rege Cadwalader ad annum 1294'' in English translates approximately as Chronicle of Wales as a sequential chronological history record of events of Wales from [[Cadwaladr|Prince Cadwalader]] to the year 1294.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|page=18}} It says there are five known manuscript copies of Llwyd's work, none in his personal handwriting. 

*''MS 1 BL, Cotton Caligula MS Avi''
:To historians that wrote on Llwyd this was the best known text. It is preceded by a [[Colophon (publishing)|colophon]] done by [[Robert Cotton (died 1559)|Sir Robert Cotton]], ''Cronica Walliae a Rege Cadwalader ad(num) 1294 Humfredo Floid authore'' with gave the title "Cronica Walliae" that Llwd's text is known by.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=4}}
*''MS 2 Bodleian Library, Ashmole MS, 847''
:This is a copy of MS 1 above that was done by [[Robert Glover (officer of arms)|Robert Glover]] around 1578. The note on the title page says "This booke was given to Mr [[John Dee | J. Dee of Mortlake]] by his cousin Mr Olyver Lloyd of the Welsh Pole 1575."{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=5}} 
*''MS 3 BL MS 48090 (Yelverton MS 99), ff. 4–105v''
:This is a handwritten copy of the Bodleian Library ''MS 2'' manuscript.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=5}}
*''MS 4 NLW, Llanstephan MS 177''
:This edition has no title. It has a treatise called "Kyfrinach y Beirdd" and the note "John ap D'd ap R'c toke possetion upon theyrsdaye being the XXjth of Majj the XV yere of the Raying of our queen Elizabeth 1573 in the hande of Ieuan ap Dav' ap Jankyn thys being wyttenessed Gryffythe mechen, John ap Owen, Gryffyth ap holl, Robert ap John Rondell, Thomas Hirllard." The manuscript is complete except for a small part related to Alfred.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=5}}
*''MS 5 NLW 23202 B'' 
:This manuscript was purchased from the [[Thomas Fairfax]] Collection by the [[National Library of Wales]] in 1993. It is preceded by a colophon text later than the manuscript itself. It has an intricate signature with text ''by Powell the original Autograph.'' The signature says "Tho. Powell." There are parts missing, deliberately left out by the copyist, that especially relate to events outside Wales. There are also parts left out related to the church and the papacy. Missing too are sections related to [[Polydore Vergil]] and other Welsh links. Because of the missing parts it is not relied on for a Llwyd reference source.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=6}}

== Commentary ==
The commentary book shows Llwyd starting his chronology of sequential records of Wales with [[Cadwaladr|Prince Cadwaladr]] of the seventh century. The first thing he explains is that he is the last British king to rule Wales, descending from the ''noble race'' of [[Troy|Trojans]]. He explains the devastating plagues that happened during his reign. He explains that the Britons had been ruled by different kings and princes for 1817 years up to Cadwaladr. Llwyd says Cadwaladr went to Rome for 5 years to study different philosophers and that he died in 688 A.D.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=63}} He then explains in "Yvor the sonne of Alan, Ina de Stirpe regia filius Kenredi sorori regis Cadwaladri" the next sequence of events that while he was in Rome ''according to the comanndement received by the angell'', he left his son [[Idwal Iwrch]], his sister and his people with ''Alan, Kinge of litle Bryttayn.''{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|pp=82–83}} Llwyd then explains that the son of Idwal Iwrch [[Rhodri Molwynog]] became the ruler of the [[Kingdom of Gwynedd]]. {{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=84}} He explains in "Rodryke the sonne of Idwall the sonne of Cadwalader" that Rhodri began his reign in the year 720.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=84}} Also in this section he details the [[Battle of Pencon]] and the [[Battle of Hehil]].{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=84}} Llwyd also talks about the [[Battle of Carno Mountain]] in 728 – see [[List of Anglo-Welsh Wars#Eighth Century|eighth-century wars]].{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=84}} In this section he also talks about the ''[[Ecclesiastical History of the English People]]'' being finished in 731 that was written by ''a great clercke that wroote manye woorkes'' named [[Bede]] from [[Monkwearmouth]].{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=84}} He says the priest Bede died in 733 A.D.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=84}} He then talks about [[Swæfberht of Essex]] and [[Saelred of Essex]].{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=84}} He also describes [[Battle Edge]] where [[Æthelbald of Mercia|King Æthelbald]] of [[Mercia]] was defeated by [[Cuthred of Wessex|King Cuthred]].{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|pp=84–5}} Llwyd then talks about King [[Rhodri Molwynog]] and that he died in 754 and left his son [[Cynan Dindaethwy]] to rule afterwards.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|pp=84–5}} 

Llwyd then goes into the next section "Kynan Tindaethwy sonne to Rodryck" beginning with the year 755. He details the [[Battle of Cenn Fabrat]] (near Seefin Mountain, Co. Limerick) where ''Dyfynwal the sonne of Teudwr'' was slain – see [[Cathussach mac Eterscélai]]. Llwyd records that [[Æthelbald of Mercia]] died in the year 757. He explains then that [[Beornred of Mercia]] succeed him. He then shows the next important event in 758 when [[Elfodd]], a Welsh bishop ''both godly and learned'' induced the standard for determining the date of [[Easter]].{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=85}} Llwyd then details in his ''historie'' the events of the year 763. He begins with [[Offa of Mercia]] becoming king and [[Heaberht of Kent]] made king of West Saxons. He later explains the [[Battle of Otford (776)|Battle of Otford]] that took place in 776. Llwyd then gives specifics for [[Offa's Dyke|the well known ditch]] Offa had built. He describes it as ''a great dyche large and deepe'' made between [[Mercia]] and [[Kingdom of Powys|Powys]] from sea to sea. In the sixteenth century it was referred to as ''Clawdh Offa'' and ''Offas Diche''. The reason he built the ditch was for protection to defend ''his country frome the incoursions of the Welshemen.''{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=86}} 

Llwyd then spells out the next important event as being ''in the year of our Lord 800'' when [[Egbert of Wessex]] (''Egbrutus'') was made king and the following year [[Coenwulf of Mercia]] (''Kenewlf'') was made king.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=86}} He says the next important event of history was when [[Cadell ap Brochfael]], the king of Powys, died in 808 and his son [[Cyngen ap Cadell]] became the new king.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=86}} Llwyd notes the next interesting event was a [[solar eclipse]] on Christmas Day in 810 and at the same time there was an unusually large death rate of cattle in Wales.{{efn-ua|The next yearc after died Elbodius Archbishop of Northwales, before whose 810 death, the sunne was sore eclipsed. In the yeare 810 was the moone eclipsed upon Christmas daie. The same yeare, S. Dauids was burnt by the West Saxons. There was also a generall morreine and death of cattell throughout all Wales. The next yeare {{Not a typo|in|suing}} died Owen the sonne of Meredyth, the sonne of Tewdos.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=86}}}} He notes also that this was the year that [[St David's Cathedral]] was ''bernt by the West Saxons.''{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=86}} Llwyd then records the death of [[Owain ap Maredudd (Dyfed)]].{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=86}} He then shows as the next dramatic event in 812 when [[Deganwy Castle]] was struck by lightning and destroyed.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=86}} 

Llwyd records as events under the section "Blethyn ap Kynvyn and Meredith ap Owen" that in 1073 [[Bleddyn ap Cynfyn#Reign|Bleddyn ap Cynfyn]] was '' traytorouselye'' and ''cowardely'' murdered by [[Rhys ab Owain]] after he reigned Wales for 13 years.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=122}} Under the section "Griffith the sonne of Kynan" Llwyd records as historical events how peacefully after the death of [[Trahaearn ap Caradog]] in 1081 [[Gruffudd ap Cynan]] ruled Northwales and [[Rhys ap Tewdwr]] ruled Southwales.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=124}} He records the history that led up to this time. One of the events he describes is the murder of [[William Walcher]] in 1080.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=124}} He describes in detail how the Northumbrians [[William Walcher#Career|killed him and his 100 men]] that accompanied him.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=124}} Later in this section Llwyd records the historical event of 1125 when [[Cadwallon ap Gruffydd]] killed his maternal uncles [[Cadwallon ap Gruffydd#Mid life|to capture]] the district [[Dyffryn Clwyd]].{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=125}}

Under the section "Owen Gwyneth sonne to Griffith ap Kynan" Llwyd records as sequential historical events how the sons of [[Gruffudd ap Cynan]] divided up the kingdoms of Wales according to custom after his death in 1137 A.D.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=151}} Llwyd explains here how [[Owain Gwynedd]] is the first to be styled [[Prince of Wales]]" starting in 1137 and that the name "king" is no longer used in British records when referring to the ruler of Wales.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=151}}

Llwyd then describes in his recordings that in the year 1146 [[Cadwallon ap Madog#Prince of Maelienydd|Cadwallon ap Madog]] captured his younger brother Einion Clud and turned him over to King [[Owain Gwynedd]], who in turn handed him over to Henry II to be imprisoned at [[Winchester]].{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=162}} He then explains how Madog soon escapes and goes back to Wales.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=162}} Llwyd reports also in this section the information that in 1160 [[Madog ap Maredudd]] died.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=161}} 

Llwyd then chronicles that in 1165 [[Dafydd ab Owain Gwynedd]] destroyed [[Tegeingl]], which at the time belonged to King Henry, and he took all the people and their possessions to the [[Vale of Clwyd|Valley of Clwyd]].{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=164}} He then describes the 1169 death of [[Owain Gwynedd]] after controlling north Wales for 32 years.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=167}} The next sequence of events he details gives an accounting of the turmoil this caused among his many children over the inheritance.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=167}} He follows this up in the next section of the events that happened in the 1170s.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|pp=167–172}}

In the section "David the sonne of Owen Gwynedh" Llwyd wrote that <blockquote>After the death of Owen his sonnes fill at debade who shulde enherite after him. For the eldest sonne borne in matrimonye Edward or Erwerth Drwyndwn was counted unmeete for his maime upon his face. And Howell who toke upon him all the rulle was a base sonne begoten upon an Irishwoman. Therefore David gathered all the power he coulde, and came against Howell, and fought with him and slewe him, and afterward enjoyed quietly the whole lande of Northwales, {{Not a typo|unt|ill}} his brother Iewerth or Edwards sonne came to age as shall hereafter appeare. And at this tyme an other of Owen Gwynedhs sonnes, named Madocke, lefte the lande in contention betwixt his bretherne, and prepared certaine shippes, with men [and] munition, and sought adventures by the seas. And sayled west levinge the cost of Irelande [so far] north that he came to a lande unknownen, where he sawe many strange things. And this lande most needes bee some parte of that lande the which the Hispaniardes affirme them selves to be the first finders, sith Hannos tyme. For by reason and order of cosmographie this lande to which Madoc came to, most needs bee somme part of Nova Hispania, or Florida. And so hit was by Britons longe afore discovered before eyther Colonus or Americus lead any Hispaniardes thyther.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|pp=167–8}}</blockquote> Peter Roberts noted that according to Dr John Dee "the Tudors had inherited a historic claim to the newfound lands in the west, first through King Arthur and then through Prince Madoc. It was Humphrey Lhuyd who, in his ‘Cronica Walliae’ (c. 1559), first publicised the legend that the Welsh prince Madog ab Owain Gwynedd (fl. 1170) had sailed across the Atlantic and discovered America."{{sfn|Bradshaw|Roberts|2003|page=29}} A return trip to Wales by Madoc and a second trip with a number of ships are additionally detailed by Llwyd.{{efn-ua|And after he had returned home and declared the pleasant and frutefull countreys that he had seene without inhabitants, and upon the countrarye parte what barreyne and wilde grounde his bretherne nevewes did murther one an other for, he prepared a number of shippes, and gote with him suche men and women as were desirouse to lyve in quietness. And taking his leave of his frendes, toke his journey thytherwarde againe wherefore hit is to be presupposed that he and his people enhabited parte of those countreys. And hit appeareth by Francys Loues that in Acujarniland yucutan, and other places, the people honoured the crosse, and that Christians had bene there before the comminge of the Hispaniardes, and because his people were not manye they followed the maners of the lande they came unto, and used the language they founde there.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=168}}}}{{sfn|Owen|1885|pp=546–560}} 

Llwyd describes historical events for the year 1170 saying, ''But to my hystorie, about the same time''{{efn-ua|But to my hystorie, about the same time,{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|page=168}}}} {{mdash}}''e.g.'', the prearranged marriage of [[Eleanor of England, Queen of Castile#Queenship|Eleanor of England, Queen of Castile]], to King [[Alfonso VIII of Castile#Marriage and Foreign Relations|Alfonso VIII of Castile]]; [[Owain Cyfeiliog]]'s land grant for the founding of the abbey of [[Strata Marcella]]; [[Richard de Clare, 2nd Earl of Pembroke#The invasion of Leinster|Richard Strongbow]]'s taking of the towns of [[Dublin]] and [[History of Waterford#Anglo Norman invasion and medieval Waterford|Waterford]] with the [[Diarmait Mac Murchada#Exile and return|King of Leinster]] (and promised marriage to [[Aoife MacMurrough#Marriage and rights|his daughter]]); and Prince [[Rhys ap Gruffydd#Welsh uprising (1164–1170)|Rhys ap Gruffydd]]'s payments to [[Henry II of England|King Henry II]] of 300 horses and 4,000 cattle and the 7 October 1170 meeting with King Henry.{{efn-ua|Elynor the Kings doughter was maryed to Alfonce, Kinge of Castell. And Richarde Strangbowe (Earle of Strigill) wen to Ireland without the Kings leave, and maryed the doughter of Diernyt, Kinge of Develyn, wherefore the Kinge ceased all his lands in Englande to his owne hands and Diernyt dyed shortely after, and was buried at Ferna. And at the end of this yere was [[Thomas Becket]] (Archebishop of Canterburye) slayne. And the yere ensuing, Rhesrince of Southwales came with a great power to Powis, and subdued Owen Keveliog the lorde therof, and toke pledges of him and returned home with muche honor. And the Kinge called his nobles to consulte aboute the enterprise of Ireland, which had bene before determined to bee taken in hand, and to his consultaciouns came messingers from Richard Strangbowe, and Earle of Strigill, and marshall of Englande, to delyver to the Kinges hands the citie of Develyn and the towne of Waterforde, with such other townes as he had by the right of his wife. Wherupon the Kinge restored to him againe his lands in England and Normandy, and made him Steewarde of Irelande, and so conclusion was taken for the Kinges viage to Ireland. And thereupon the Lord Rhes came to the Kinge, and the Kinge received him to his peace, and confirmed him all that he had and therefore Rhes paid the Kinge 300 horses and 4000 oxen, and gave him 14 pledges.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|pages=168–9}}}} Llwyd then explains the November 1170 conspiracy to kill Archbishop [[Thomas Becket]] which happened then right after Christmas of the same year.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=169}} He names [[William de Tracy]], [[Richard le Breton]], and  [[Reginald Fitzurse#Assassination of Becket|Reginald Fitzurse]] as three of the four knights that did the murder.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=170}}

Llwyd then gives the chronological historical events going from 1171 and going into 1172. He records the events of King Henry II visiting [[Laugharne#History|Laugharne]] in 1172 on his return from Ireland and made peace with Prince Rhys.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=170}} He then describes the [[Laugharne#Laugharne Charter|Laugharne Charter]] that was made between them at this time.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=170}} Llwyd then records the ''traytorousely'' and ''cowardly'' 1174 murder of [[Iorwerth Drwyndwn]].{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=170}} 
He then gives as a summary how Dafydd ab Owain Gwynedd in the same year imprisons his brother Rhodri and puts him in shackles to take away his inherited lands.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=172}} Llwyd then states as the next sequence of events how in 1175 Howell, son of Iorwerth, takes Owen Penkarn (his maternal uncle) prisoner, pokes out his eyes and castrates him.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=171}} He references this back to the history records of Matthew Paris.{{sfn|Lhwyd|Powell|1811|page=170}} Llwyd then explains that in 1176 [[William II of Sicily]] married [[Joan of England, Queen of Sicily|Joan the daughter of King Henry II]].{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=174}} 

Llwyd then notes the records that in 1179 [[King Henry II of England]] bought the [[County of La Marche]] in France for ''6000 of silver'' and put [[Hubert de Burgh, 1st Earl of Kent]] in charge of it.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=174}} Llwyd's manuscript contains a report regarding an alleged 1179 discovery at [[Glastonbury Abbey]] at the [[Avalon#Connection to Glastonbury|island of Avalon]] (a/k/a Island of Apples) of the burial place of [[King Arthur]] and his wife. He describes it as located fifteen feet down in the ground in an elder [[treetrunk coffin]] with a cross of lead. It is referenced to Matthew Paris as being recorded about 10 years after the discovery. The inscription on the cross was recorded to be
<poem>
:::''Hic jacet sepultus inclitus rex Arthurus in insula Avalonia'' – Powell spelling.{{sfn|Lhwyd|Powell|1811|page=173}}
:::''Hic jacet sepultus inclytus Rex Arthurus in insula Avalonia'' – Williams spelling.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=174}}
:::Here lies buried the renowned King Arthur on the island of Avalon – English translation from the Latin. 
</poem>

Llwyd details the bones found as '' mervelouse biggenesse '' and the probable cause of Arthur's death (a hard blow to the head).{{efn-ua|The bones were of a mervelouse biggenesse, and in the scule were 10 wounds, of which one was great and seamed to bee his deathes wounde.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=174}}}} He further describes the queen's hair as being blonde. He records that clues to King Arthur's burial location were found because of a poem of a [[bard]] that [[Henry II of England|King Henry II]] heard at [[Pembroke Castle]].{{efn-ua|This yeare the bones of noble king Arthur and Gwenhouar his wife were found in the He of Avalon (Matt.Paris), without the Abbie of Glastenburie, fifteene foote within the earth, in a hollow elder tree, and ouer the bones was a stone and a crosse of lead, with a Ran. Cest. writing turned towards the stone, wherein were ingrauen these words: "Hic jacet sepultus inclitus rex Arthurus in insula Avalonia." The bones were of maruelous bignes, and in the scull were ten wounds, of which ten yeares, after this one was great, and seemed to be his deaths wound: the Queenes haire was to the time, sight faire and yellowe, but assoone as it was touched it fell to ashes. This graue was found by meanes of a Bardh or Poet, whom the king heard at Penbrooke declare in a song the worthie actes of that noble prince, and the place of his buriall. {{sfn|Lhwyd|Powell|1811|page=173}}}} 

Llwyd then in a chronological sequence shows the year 1182 as that when [[Henry the Lion|Henry duke of Saxony]] was exiled from Germany and stayed with [[Henry II of England|King Henry II]], his father-in-law, in [[Normandy]]. In 1184 is born a son, later to be called [[William of Winchester, Lord of Luneburg]]. He also lists 1183 as the year [[Henry the Young King|Henry the young King]] died.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=175}} Llwyd then tells of the murder of [[Hugh de Lacy, Lord of Meath#Death, aftermath and legacy|Hugh de Lacy, Lord of Meath]] in 1186 and [[John, King of England|Prince John]] is sent over to Ireland to take possession of his lands and returns at Christmas.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=175}} The year 1186 is also the time Llwyd lists as when [[Geoffrey II, Duke of Brittany]] dies, leaving behind a daughter and a wife pregnant with the future [[Arthur I, Duke of Brittany]].{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=175}} He references these 1180s events back to the historian Matthew Paris.{{sfn|Lhwyd|Powell|1811|page=174}}

Llwyd then talks about the year 1187 as being the time when [[Owain Brogyntyn]] was murdered at [[Carreg Cennen Castle]]. This same year Llwyd shows of when [[Maelgwn ap Rhys]] for the first time appears in the historical record bringing his power against [[Tenby#History|Tenby]] and by brute force took the town burning it down.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=175}} He then shows the next important time as 1189, being the time when [[Henry II of England]] died.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=175}} He explains then his son [[Richard I of England|Richard]] becomes King of England.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=175}} This same year Llwyd explains as being when [[The Lord Rhys#Final campaigns (1189–1196)|Rhys ap Gruffydd]] captured the castles of St. Clear's, [[Laugharne Castle|Laugharne]], and [[Llansteffan Castle|Llansteffan]].{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=176}} He further explains that this is when Lord Rhys' [[Maelgwn ap Rhys|son Maelgwn]] is taken prisoner.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=176}}
Llwyd goes on to say this is when [[Richard I of England#King and Crusader|Richard I of England]] was officially made Bishop of Durham and [[Duke of Normandy]].{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=176}} Llwyd then points out that Richard was captured in 1192 near [[Vienna]] by [[Leopold V, Duke of Austria]], who turns him over to [[Henry VI, Holy Roman Emperor|Henry the Emperor]] that asked for a 20,000 mark ransom.{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=177}}

Llwyd then writes about what historian [[Nicholas Trivet]] recorded for the year 1270. He talks about [[Llywelyn ap Gruffudd]] and Gruffudd ap Madog (1236–70) Lord of Bromfield. He then ends his manuscript in 1295 with the history of [[Madog ap Llywelyn]] and the [[Battle of Maes Moydog]]. He claims then that there was nothing worthy done in Wales after this that otherwise could not "bee redde in the Englishe Cronicle".{{sfn|Llwyd|2002|p=7}}

